		<content type="html" xml:base="https://love2d.org/forums/viewtopic.php?p=259109#p259109"><![CDATA[
<blockquote class="uncited"><div>Ehhh, here's something weird.<br>From my tests, that Lua-based method in the OP is slightly faster than the Box2D one. Point for LuaJIT I guess, it's probably optimizing that function amazingly. I honestly thought the C++ one would be faster.</div></blockquote>I'm not too surprised. In LuaJIT, external function calls via standard Lua (as opposed to via FFI) either prevent compilation, or require trace stitching (meaning, switch to interpreter mode, run the function, switch back to compiled mode and resume), both of which are slow. I already got <a href="https://love2d.org/forums/viewtopic.php?p=230629#p23062" class="postlink">caught by that trap</a> with the transform functions when testing cam11.<br><br>I'm concerned about this condition in your code:<br><div class="codebox"><p>Code: </p><pre><code>        if py ~= lastY then</code></pre></div>Does that mean that polygons with <del>vertical</del> <span style="text-decoration:underline">horizontal</span> segments can't be used?<br><br>It's likely that allowing the division by zero will be harmless and will make it work. Infinity will be properly propagated and the check for x &lt; infinity should return the expected result.<br><br>I think the test can be rewritten without divisions, though. If we unfold deltaX_div_deltaY as (lastX - px) / (lastY - py), then:<br><br>x &lt; (y - py) * (lastX - px) / (lastY - py) + px<br>is equivalent to<br>x - px &lt; (y - py) * (lastX - px) / (lastY - py)<br>which is equivalent to<br>(x - px) * (lastY - py) &lt; (y - py) * (lastX - px)<br><br>But beware the sign of lastY - py because the last equivalence only holds if it's positive.<br><br>Edit: In fact, that's pretty much what I did in my version.<br>Edit2: oops, not vertical but horizontal segments<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="https://love2d.org/forums/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=137168">pgimeno</a> — Sun Mar 24, 2024 2:20 pm</p><hr />
